{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775872462010,"sessionID":"ses_285c0e4f5ffelpq9u3QY0wGlKK","part":{"id":"prt_d7a3f3e66001cI4aO06VJ0g1yz","messageID":"msg_d7a3f3018001b4VpASpo3o7YNm","sessionID":"ses_285c0e4f5ffelpq9u3QY0wGlKK","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_38437d8c6c0d453d8188aac9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-030/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-030/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-030: Helm Chart 模板与 Values\n2: \n3: ## Summary\n4: \n5: Implement the Helm Chart templates and values configuration for deploying AgentCube to Kubernetes, providing a reusable, configurable deployment mechanism for the Workload Manager, Router, optional Volcano scheduler, and associated RBAC resources.\n6: \n7: ## Purpose\n8: \n9: ### Background\n10: \n11: AgentCube requires a standardized deployment mechanism to Kubernetes clusters. Currently, the system lacks a formal Helm chart for production deployments. The deployment/design.md and deployment/spec.md documents define the expected chart structure, but the actual template files need implementation.\n12: \n13: The Helm chart enables:\n14: - Reproducible deployments across environments\n15: - Configuration management via values.yaml\n16: - Namespace-scoped installations\n17: - Optional components (RBAC, Volcano scheduler)\n18: - CRD lifecycle management\n19: \n20: ### Goal\n21: \n22: Create a complete Helm 3 chart at `manifests/charts/base/` that:\n23: - Renders Workload Manager Deployment + Service\n24: - Renders Router Deployment + Service\n25: - Renders RBAC resources (ClusterRole, ClusterRoleBinding, optional Role)\n26: - Optionally renders Volcano agent scheduler resources\n27: - Ships CRDs for AgentCube runtime custom resources\n28: - Provides comprehensive values.yaml for configuration\n29: \n30: ### Value\n31: \n32: - **Standardization**: Follows Kubernetes community conventions\n33: - **Operational Efficiency**: Single command deployment with configurable parameters\n34: - **Flexibility**: Optional components and extensive customization via values\n35: - **Security**: Proper RBAC with minimal privileges\n36: - **Maintainability**: Template-driven, version-controlled deployments\n37: \n38: ---\n39: \n40: ## Scope\n41: \n42: ### In-Scope\n43: \n44: | Component | Path | Description |\n45: |-----------|------|-------------|\n46: | Chart.yaml | `manifests/charts/base/Chart.yaml` | Helm chart metadata (name: agentcube, version: 0.1.0) |\n47: | values.yaml | `manifests/charts/base/values.yaml` | Default configuration values |\n48: | WorkloadManager templates | `manifests/charts/base/templates/workloadmanager.yaml` | Deployment + Service |\n49: | Router templates | `manifests/charts/base/templates/agentcube-router.yaml` | Deployment + Service |\n50: | RBAC templates | `manifests/charts/base/templates/rbac/workloadmanager.yaml` | ServiceAccount, ClusterRole, ClusterRoleBinding |\n51: | RBAC templates | `manifests/charts/base/templates/rbac-router.yaml` | Optional Role + RoleBinding (conditional) |\n52: | Volcano scheduler templates | `manifests/charts/base/templates/volcano-agent-scheduler-development.yaml` | Optional scheduler resources |\n53: | CRD manifests | `manifests/charts/base/crds/` | agentruntimes.runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh, codeinterpreters.runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh |\n54: \n55: ### Out-of-Scope\n56: \n57: - Kubernetes cluster provisioning\n58: - Ingress configuration\n59: - Prometheus/Grafana monitoring stack\n60: - Redis deployment (external dependency)\n61: - Application-level secrets management beyond RBAC\n62: - Multi-cluster deployment strategies\n63: - Helm hook-based upgrade migrations\n64: \n65: ---\n66: \n67: ## Impact Analysis\n68: \n69: ### Dependencies\n70: \n71: | Dependency | Purpose | Status |\n72: |------------|---------|--------|\n73: | Helm 3 | Chart rendering and installation | Required |\n74: | Kubernetes 1.19+ | API versions used | Required |\n75: | Redis | Session storage (external) | Required at runtime |\n76: | agent-sandbox CRDs | Sandbox CRD definitions | Required for WorkloadManager ClusterRole |\n77: \n78: ### Upstream\n79: \n80: - `deployment/design.md` — Helm chart specification\n81: - `deployment/spec.md` — Deployment requirements\n82: - `pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1/` — CRD type definitions (source for generated CRDs)\n83: - `docker/Dockerfile` — Workload Manager image build\n84: - `docker/Dockerfile.router` — Router image build\n85: \n86: ### Downstream Consumers\n87: \n88: 1. **Operators** — Deploy AgentCube via Helm\n89: 2. **CI/CD pipelines** — Automated deployments via `helm upgrade --install`\n90: 3. **E2E tests** — Use Helm for test cluster setup\n91: 4. **Documentation** — Reference Helm values for configuration\n92: \n93: ### Risks\n94: \n95: | Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n96: |------|----------|------------|\n97: | CRD version mismatch | High | Ship CRDs with chart; require controller-gen v0.17.2 |\n98: | RBAC permissions too broad | Medium | Follow least-privilege; document required permissions |\n99: | Template rendering errors | Medium | Include Helm linting in CI |\n100: | Upgrade path complexity | Low | Document migration steps; use Helm hooks if needed |\n101: | Image pull failures | Medium | Support imagePullSecrets in values |\n102: \n103: ---\n104: \n105: ## Alternatives Considered\n106: \n107: ### Option 1: Raw YAML manifests (Not Selected)\n108: \n109: **Pros**: Simple, no templating dependency, version control friendly\n110: **Cons**: No parameterization, duplication across environments, harder to maintain, no Helm ecosystem integration\n111: \n112: ### Option 2: Kustomize (Not Selected)\n113: \n114: **Pros**: Native Kubernetes configuration management, overlays for environments\n115: **Cons**: Less widely adopted in operator tooling, Helm more common for single-command installs, additional learning curve\n116: \n117: ### Option 3: Ansible/Kubectl (Not Selected)\n118: \n119: **Pros**: Flexible, idempotent\n120: **Cons**: Additional tool dependency, less declarative, harder to version and rollback\n121: \n122: ### Option 4: Helm 3 chart (Selected)\n123: \n124: **Pros**: Industry standard, extensive ecosystem, values parameterization, rollback support, Helm hooks for lifecycle\n125: **Cons**: Templating complexity, requires Helm knowledge\n126: \n127: ---\n128: \n129: ## Technical Design\n130: \n131: ### Chart Structure\n132: \n133: ```\n134: manifests/charts/base/\n135: ├── Chart.yaml\n136: ├── values.yaml\n137: ├── templates/\n138: │   ├── workloadmanager.yaml\n139: │   ├── agentcube-router.yaml\n140: │   ├── rbac/\n141: │   │   └── workloadmanager.yaml\n142: │   ├── rbac-router.yaml (conditional)\n143: │   └── volcano-agent-scheduler-development.yaml (conditional)\n144: └── crds/\n145:     ├── runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh_agentruntimes.yaml\n146:     └── runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh_codeinterpreters.yaml\n147: ```\n148: \n149: ### values.yaml Key Tree\n150: \n151: | Path | Type | Default |\n152: |------|------|---------|\n153: | `imagePullSecrets` | array | `[]` |\n154: | `redis.addr` | string | `\"\"` (required) |\n155: | `redis.password` | string | `\"\"` |\n156: | `router.replicas` | int | `1` |\n157: | `router.image.*` | string | `ghcr.io/volcano-sh/agentcube-router:latest` |\n158: | `router.service.*` | object | ClusterIP:8080 |\n159: | `router.resources.*` | object | CPU/memory limits |\n160: | `router.rbac.create` | bool | `false` |\n161: | `workloadmanager.replicas` | int | `1` |\n162: | `workloadmanager.image.*` | string | `ghcr.io/volcano-sh/workloadmanager:latest` |\n163: | `workloadmanager.service.*` | object | ClusterIP:8080 |\n164: | `workloadmanager.resources.*` | object | CPU/memory limits |\n165: | `volcano.scheduler.enabled` | bool | `false` |\n166: \n167: ### Template Logic\n168: \n169: #### WorkloadManager Deployment\n170: - Uses `workloadmanager.replicas` count\n171: - Sets `AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` via downward API\n172: - Injects `REDIS_ADDR`, `REDIS_PASSWORD` from values\n173: - Health probes: HTTP GET `/health`\n174: - Resource limits from values\n175: \n176: #### Router Deployment\n177: - Uses `router.replicas` count\n178: - Sets `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL` = `http://workloadmanager.{{.Release.Namespace}}.svc.cluster.local:{{ workloadmanager.service.port }}`\n179: - Injects Redis env vars\n180: - Health probes: `/health/live`, `/health/ready`\n181: - Conditional RBAC based on `router.rbac.create`\n182: \n183: #### RBAC\n184: - ClusterRole `workloadmanager`: CRUD on sandboxes, sandboxclaims, codeinterpreters, agentruntimes, pods, secrets; tokenreviews\n185: - Optional Role `router`: secret management in namespace\n186: \n187: #### Volcano Scheduler (Conditional)\n188: - Rendered only when `volcano.scheduler.enabled: true`\n189: - Includes ServiceAccount, ConfigMap, ClusterRole, ClusterRoleBinding, Service, Deployment\n190: \n191: ### CRD Shipment\n192: \n193: CRDs installed via chart's `crds/` directory:\n194: - `agentruntimes.runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh`\n195: - `codeinterpreters.runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh`\n196: \n197: ---\n198: \n199: ## Implementation Plan\n200: \n201: ### Phase 1: Chart scaffolding\n202: \n203: - [ ] Create `manifests/charts/base/Chart.yaml`\n204: - [ ] Create `manifests/charts/base/values.yaml` with documented defaults\n205: - [ ] Create `manifests/charts/base/templates/.gitkeep`\n206: - [ ] Create `manifests/charts/base/crds/.gitkeep`\n207: \n208: ### Phase 2: Core templates\n209: \n210: - [ ] Create `templates/workloadmanager.yaml` (Deployment + Service)\n211: - [ ] Create `templates/agentcube-router.yaml` (Deployment + Service)\n212: - [ ] Add health probe configurations\n213: - [ ] Add resource limits templating\n214: \n215: ### Phase 3: RBAC templates\n216: \n217: - [ ] Create `templates/rbac/workloadmanager.yaml` (ServiceAccount, ClusterRole, ClusterRoleBinding)\n218: - [ ] Create `templates/rbac-router.yaml` (conditional Role + RoleBinding)\n219: - [ ] Define ClusterRole rules matching agent-sandbox and AgentCube CRDs\n220: \n221: ### Phase 4: Optional components\n222: \n223: - [ ] Create `templates/volcano-agent-scheduler-development.yaml` (conditional)\n224: - [ ] Add ConfigMap with agent-scheduler.conf\n225: - [ ] Add Volcano ClusterRole rules\n226: \n227: ### Phase 5: CRDs\n228: \n229: - [ ] Add CRD manifests to `crds/` directory\n230: - [ ] Verify CRD API group and version\n231: \n232: ### Phase 6: Validation\n233: \n234: - [ ] Add Helm linting to Makefile\n235: - [ ] Test template rendering with `helm template`\n236: - [ ] Verify RBAC rule correctness\n237: \n238: ---\n239: \n240: ## Acceptance Criteria\n241: \n242: | ID | Scenario | Expected Result |\n243: |----|----------|-----------------|\n244: | HELM-001 | Chart.yaml renders | Valid Helm chart with name=agentcube, version=0.1.0 |\n245: | HELM-002 | Default values.yaml | Contains all documented keys with correct defaults |\n246: | HELM-003 | WorkloadManager deployment | Deployment with replicas from values, correct image, env vars |\n247: | HELM-004 | WorkloadManager service | Service with correct port mapping |\n248: | HELM-005 | Router deployment | Deployment with WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL correctly constructed |\n249: | HELM-006 | Router service | Service with type from values |\n250: | HELM-007 | RBAC rendered | ServiceAccount + ClusterRole + ClusterRoleBinding present |\n251: | HELM-008 | Optional router RBAC | Role rendered only when router.rbac.create=true |\n252: | HELM-009 | Optional Volcano | Scheduler resources rendered only when enabled |\n253: | HELM-010 | CRDs present | Both agentruntime and codeinterpreter CRDs in crds/ |\n254: | HELM-011 | Helm lint passes | `helm lint manifests/charts/base` succeeds |\n255: | HELM-012 | Template dry-run | `helm template test manifests/charts/base` renders without error |\n256: \n257: ---\n258: \n259: ## Timeline Estimate\n260: \n261: | Phase | Effort |\n262: |-------|--------|\n263: | Chart scaffolding | 1 hour |\n264: | Core templates | 3 hours |\n265: | RBAC templates | 2 hours |\n266: | Optional components | 2 hours |\n267: | CRDs | 1 hour |\n268: | Validation & testing | 2 hours |\n269: | **Total** | **11 hours** |\n270: \n271: ---\n272: \n273: ## Relationship to Other ARs\n274: \n275: AR-030 provides the deployment mechanism for all AgentCube components:\n276: \n277: - AR-027, AR-028 — SDK clients depend on deployed services\n278: - AR-029 — HTTP client layer communicates with Workload Manager and Router\n279: - The Go binaries (workload-manager, router, agentd, picod) require this chart for Kubernetes deployment\n\n(End of file - total 279 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-030: Helm Chart 模板与 Values\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement the Helm Chart templates and values configuration for deploying AgentCube to Kubernetes, providing a reusable, configurable deployment mechanism for the Workload Manager, Router, optional Volcano scheduler, and associated RBAC resources.\n\n## Purpose\n\n### Background\n\nAgentCube requires a standardized deployment mechanism to Kubernetes clusters. Currently, the system lacks a formal Helm chart for production deployments. The deployment/design.md and deployment/spec.md documents define the expected chart structure, but the actual template files need implementation.\n\nThe Helm chart enables:\n- Reproducible deployments across environments\n- Configuration management via values.yaml\n- Namespace-scoped installations\n- Optional components (RBAC, Volcano scheduler)\n- CRD lifecycle management\n\n### Goal","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-030/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775872461977,"end":1775872462007}}}}
